00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:26.220 position:56%
begins with my own research on the
Benedictine Monastery of [inaudible]

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:30.900
and the efforts of two 18th
century historians, one a jesuit,

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:35.260
Raymundo Diosdado Caballero, who
was living in Rome and the other,

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:39.820
the Augustinian Francisco Mendez
living in Madrid were attempting

00:10:39.820 --> 00:10:44.670 position:56%
to uncover the early printing
history of Spain of the 15th century

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:49.510
as they engaged in a historical
debate at the close of the 18th.

00:10:49.510 --> 00:10:52.600
They were particularly
interested in the printing press

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:59.990
that [inaudible] operated by
[inaudible] between 1499 and 1500.

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:01.750
[Inaudible] not only boasted one

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:06.320
of the finest Medieval manuscript
collections in Europe at the time

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:10.430
but also one of the best
rare book collections.

00:11:10.430 --> 00:11:13.650
It was also one of the most
important early prolific centers

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:16.620
of printing at the end
of the 15th century.

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:22.460
Now being good historians, both
of them, unable to travel wrote

00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:28.690
to the archivist at Montserrat,
Friar Benet Ribas i Calaf

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:32.290
who was asked to provide them
any type of information he could

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:36.520
from their manuscripts and archives
regarding the printing press.

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:40.280
Friar Benet who was an exceptional
historian himself dug deep

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:41.990
into the manuscript archive

00:11:41.990 --> 00:11:46.110
and actually found the original
contracts that were written

00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:51.820
by Garcia [inaudible]
and Johann Luschner,

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:54.570
the printer who had taken
his press to the [inaudible].

00:11:54.570 --> 00:12:01.680
He found those documents, and he
first transcribed and sent them

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:09.860 position:56%
to [inaudible] in Rome and later
again to Madrid to Francisco Mendez.

00:12:09.860 --> 00:12:13.480
Those two historians in
turn printed selections

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:17.520
of those letters [inaudible]
in different versions

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:20.300
in their own respective books.

00:12:20.300 --> 00:12:23.270
The fact that both historians
recorded distinct original

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:28.370
transcriptions that is a copy of
original documents provided me

00:12:28.370 --> 00:12:30.920
as a young scholar with
this amazing opportunity

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:34.980
if I could only find those
original manuscripts.

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:37.290
My dissertation would
have been complete

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:39.950
in much less time than it was.

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:46.460
Sadly, however, Montserrat's
library was destroyed.

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:51.060 position:56%
Between 1808 and 1812, major battles
took place during the Peninsula War

00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:56.390
and Napoleonic troops burned the
library to the ground in 1812.

00:12:56.390 --> 00:12:59.210
And as a result, over
10,000 manuscripts

00:12:59.210 --> 00:13:01.630
and early printed books
went up in flames

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:04.920
and countless manuscript
archival records no longer exist

00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.290
and were destroyed.

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:10.420
Everything that we know about the
printing press of Johann Luschner

00:13:10.420 --> 00:13:12.150
and its operations all

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:16.450
of the manuscripts recorded those
activities are now only preserved

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:21.120
in copies found in
18th century books.

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:28.090
The second Benedictine one is
probably more famous to you.

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:30.970
These very famous pictures,
of course, of the destruction

00:13:30.970 --> 00:13:33.560
of Montecassino from 1944.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:35.470
It was at this time, of course,

00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:37.830
that something really
remarkable was happening.

00:13:37.830 --> 00:13:40.490
Libraries, of course, in Europe
during World Wars had been

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:42.070
vulnerable to destruction.

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:44.350
One only has to remember what
happened to the University Library

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:47.770
in [inaudible] which was
destroyed in World War I.

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:50.820
Here there was an interesting
debate that took place in 1944

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:53.950
when two German officers
showed up at the [inaudible]

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:57.900
and basically begged the monks to
relocate their library in order

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:02.440
to preserve it because of the
threat of allied bombing raids.

00:14:02.440 --> 00:14:06.450
Maltese archivist librarian at
the time, Father Mauro Inguanez

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:08.850
who was born in the
city of [inaudible],

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:11.160
argued that the library
should not be moved.

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:13.390
In fact, he was very
worried because of the rumors

00:14:13.390 --> 00:14:15.910
that the Germans had been
confiscating libraries

00:14:15.910 --> 00:14:19.580
and deporting them to
Germany never to return again.

00:14:19.580 --> 00:14:23.480 position:56%
His [inaudible] at the time, Tommaso
Leccisotti, argued on the contrary

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:26.230
and said that we must move them,
that he wasn't really confident

00:14:26.230 --> 00:14:29.250
in allied bombing, particularly
because of the evidence

00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:30.550
of what had taken place

00:14:30.550 --> 00:14:33.430
in the southern Italian
peninsula at the time.

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:37.130
Fortunately for us, the
group got together, the monks

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:41.820
and their chapter, and they voted
to move the library to [inaudible]

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:49.410 position:56%
in 1944 and as a result, the state
and Monastic library that was housed

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:52.290
at Montecassino was preserved.

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:57.310
Father Maurio Inguanez was,
of course, extremely happy

00:14:57.310 --> 00:14:58.690
about the preservation
of the library

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:00.620
and the stroke of luck that he had.

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:04.790
In fact, we singularly owe
him the existence of the ashes

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:09.840
of [inaudible] which he had put
into his own duffle bag and hidden

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:12.730
in a secret part of the library
and then transported them

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:15.050
to the British Embassy
after the war.

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:17.570
This is a fun little story to add.

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:20.880
The destruction of the libraries
we can see here, of course,

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:23.470
was a great tragedy, although
the books were preserved.

00:15:23.470 --> 00:15:27.950
Father Maurio Inguanez left to
the United States to raise funds

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:31.030
