of the Benedictine
manuscript libraries in Europe.

00:16:23.120 --> 00:16:25.830
Now it's not as if these type
of projects were unheard of.

00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:27.550
We already had the
Knights of Columbus working

00:16:27.550 --> 00:16:30.670
on microfilming the Vatican
Library and the Lutheran Churches

00:16:30.670 --> 00:16:33.720
of America had begun filming
the works of Martin Luther

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:37.120
and the early Protestants
in Germany and Austria.

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:39.860
But there was no organization
that had dedicated itself

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:43.170
to the preservation of
small and remote libraries

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:47.180 position:56%
that were vulnerable not only to the
fact that the libraries might close

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:50.130
but also to the fact that these
libraries were often neglected

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:52.900
for conservation purposes.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:59.640
Father Colman at this time enlisted
his -- to help with this endeavor.

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:04.710
His [inaudible] Oliver Kapsner
who was at this time the librarian

00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:07.770
at Catholic University of America
and also research librarian

00:17:07.770 --> 00:17:10.110
at the Library of Congress.

00:17:10.110 --> 00:17:12.740 position:56%
Father Oliver Kapsner had
firsthand witness of the destruction

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:15.490
of Europe having been a
chaplain in World War II

00:17:15.490 --> 00:17:18.610
in the European theater
of operations.

00:17:18.610 --> 00:17:21.390
I believe he was at
the Battle of the Bulge

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:24.400
and therefore could see
firsthand the greatest destruction

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:30.380
of European culture that took
place during that campaign.

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:34.230
These two gentlemen, of
course, first went to Italy.

00:17:34.230 --> 00:17:37.890
It was a logical place for them to
begin their preservation efforts,

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:41.030
but initially their
work was frustrated

00:17:41.030 --> 00:17:45.110
and Montecassino did not open
their doors to their preservation.

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:49.740
Instead, they went to
Austria and later to Germany.

00:17:49.740 --> 00:17:52.850
Austria was a obvious place to go.

00:17:52.850 --> 00:17:54.470
Not only did it have
some of the greatest

00:17:54.470 --> 00:17:57.270
and most beautiful Benedictine
libraries in the world,

00:17:57.270 --> 00:17:59.010
but at this time it was sandwiched

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:02.680
between both the Warsaw
Pact and NATO.

00:18:02.680 --> 00:18:04.720
Austria was vulnerable to invasion

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:07.440
because it wouldn't immediately
trigger the NATO alliance.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:10.850
You have to remember this was,
of course, taking place in 1964

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:13.810
and 1965 at the height
of the Cold War.

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:19.830 position:56%
And it was at this time in 1965 when
the [inaudible] opened his doors

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:24.240
to Father Kapsner and began
the microfilm project,

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:27.520
which has now been going
strong for over 50 years now

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:29.820
that we are using digital
technology.

00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:35.150
This early work that was undertaken
by Father Oliver Kapsner in Austria

00:18:35.150 --> 00:18:39.290
and Germany lasted
until the early 1970's.

00:18:39.290 --> 00:18:44.340
And it was at this time that the
then director, Dr. Julian Plant,

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:49.810
envisioned HMML's work
into something much bigger.

00:18:49.810 --> 00:18:54.270 position:56%
What began as the monastic
manuscript microfilm project quickly

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:58.870
became the Hill Monastic
Manuscript Library.

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:02.950
And it was at this time in
discussions first with Ethiopia

00:19:02.950 --> 00:19:07.230
with Emperor [inaudible] and then
in Spain and then, of course,

00:19:07.230 --> 00:19:10.630
with Malta that the Hill
Museum began a worldwide effort

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:14.210
to preserve endangered
library collections.

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:15.510
The first one, of course,

00:19:15.510 --> 00:19:18.440
that expanded beyond Europe
was actually in Ethiopia.

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:22.820 position:56%
His holiness [inaudible] and Emperor
[inaudible] were very worried

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:26.110
about the state of Ethiopian
libraries in particular

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.440
in the cultural trafficking
of objects.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:31.220
They were also worried about
an uprising and some form

00:19:31.220 --> 00:19:36.090 position:56%
of communist revolution in Ethiopia,
and therefore thought it imperative

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:39.820
to start preserving their
libraries before it was too late.

00:19:39.820 --> 00:19:45.830
It must be remembered that in 1973
Spain, of course, was still dealing

00:19:45.830 --> 00:19:49.320
with the idea of what might
happen if Franco had passed away.

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:52.990
Given the complexity and
violence of the Spanish Civil War,

00:19:52.990 --> 00:19:57.880
destruction of the Spanish cultural
heritage was in obvious peril.

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:01.290
Malta, of course, in 1973 was
going through its own transition.

00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:04.350
It was strategically
located in the Mediterranean

00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:06.250
and with the conflicts
going on in the world,

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:10.930 position:56%
one would not know what would happen
if it became an object of conflict

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:15.580
as a competition between the
Warsaw states and also NATO.

00:20:15.580 --> 00:20:18.620
To kind of put this
into perspective,

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:21.910
you can imagine what was going
through the people's minds

00:20:21.910 --> 00:20:24.010
at HMML in the early 1970's.

00:20:24.010 --> 00:20:28.190
The University of Complutense
in Madrid between 1936

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:35.670
and 1939 lost 80,000 books,
80,000 in one single institution.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:40.600
Malta itself received more
bombs between 1940 and 1943

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:45.090
in a geographical area than
any other place in Europe.

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:49.150
What might happen to those library
collections if war began again?

00:20:49.150 --> 00:20:55.040
To kind of put all of this into
perspective, I'm going to focus

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:58.670
on a few unique objects,
which thanks to the efforts

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:01.720
of HMML we now can actually trace.

00:21:01.720 --> 00:21:05.290
One of them was a microfilm
of this 18th century Bible.

00:21:05.290 --> 00:21:08.770
It's actually not a complete
Bible but selections photographed

00:21:08.770 --> 00:21:13.700
in the 1970's known as EMML 7014.

00:21:13.700 --> 00:21:18.960
This Bible disappeared only to
resurface several years later

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:21.610
at the National Library of Norway.

00:21:21.610 --> 00:21:24.220
And thanks to our microfilming
process,

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:26.820
you can see I've actually flipped
into the modern era already.

00:21:26.820 --> 00:21:29.830
Thanks to our microfilming process,
we are actually able to identify

00:21:29.830 --> 00:21:34.270
and locate this Bible and
create a strong connection

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:38.750 position:56%
between its original owners in
Ethiopia and also maintain its place

00:21:38.750 --> 00:21:40.950
in the National Library of Norway.

00:21:40.950 --> 00:21:42.940
Therefore, what began as a project

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:47.530 position:56%
to preserve cultural heritage helped
us actually locate trafficked --

00:21:47.530 --> 00:21:50.040
illegally trafficked manuscripts.

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:54.240
This is something that
continues to today.

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:57.560
One can only turn to Ebay
and see the cultural heritage

00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:02.390
from around the world, Ethiopia,
Syria, Egypt, the Middle East,

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:08.830
Afghanistan, the market for
manuscripts is ever increasing

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:11.080
and because of their uniqueness ,

00:22:11.080 --> 00:22:15.080
hey are objects of
desire on the market.

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:21.000
A second example which I
find even more interesting

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.580
to my mind is this really
unique cover that you can see

00:22:24.580 --> 00:22:28.230
from our 2010 newsletter,
Illuminations.

00:22:28.230 --> 00:22:30.930
You can see here an the
11th century Latin Bible

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:33.770
that was produced in Spain.

00:22:33.770 --> 00:22:36.630
It's remarkable because this
Bible was actually destroyed

00:22:36.630 --> 00:22:40.140
in the [inaudible] Library in 1937.

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:43.880
What you see in color is the
one fragment that remains

00:22:43.880 --> 00:22:48.380
from this very rare
[inaudible] manuscript.

00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:51.500
In 2010, Dr. Hugh Hone [assumed
spelling] contacted HMML

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:54.990
and wondered, "Did we have a
microfilm of this manuscript?"

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:57.590
Which seemed a bit odd because
we hadn't actually done any work

00:22:57.590 --> 00:22:59.460
in the 1930's, but he
wondered if somehow

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:01.890
or another there was
anything that we had.

00:23:01.890 --> 00:23:04.570
There were some plates floating
around, but he really wanted

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:07.020
to know was there something.

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:11.990 position:56%
And in fact what ended up happening
is in 1979 unbeknownst to all of us,

00:23:11.990 --> 00:23:14.820
Dr. Julian Plant had
engaged in this process

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:19.230
of buying individual microfilms to
support HMML's overall collections,

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:21.940
trying to find copies of
all of the [inaudible]

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:25.520
so that people could
study the manuscripts

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:28.530
and not just the plates at HMML.

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.120
In so doing, he actually purchased
a film from the [inaudible]

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:36.390
in Madridin 1979, which
was Kodak's 31 [inaudible]

00:23:36.390 --> 00:23:42.680
which was taken before
the Spanish Civil War

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:45.990
and housed in the national library.

00:23:45.990 --> 00:23:48.860
The National Library of
Madrid or the National Library

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:51.740
of Spain sent us there one
unique [inaudible] instead

00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:54.180
of making a duplicate.

00:23:54.180 --> 00:23:59.350
So we have the only microfilm of
the world of this lost manuscript,

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:01.200
which was now being
able to be studied

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:03.380
and put together with the original.

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:09.520
My third and final example which
I can smile at my colleage,

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:14.600 position:56%
Dr. Karen Ruff, over there to the
left is actually now found in Malta.

00:24:14.600 --> 00:24:16.390
This, of course, is
a digital manuscript,

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:19.960
which we photographed
earlier this year.

00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:24.670
This manuscript was discovered
in a drawer upstairs and found

00:24:24.670 --> 00:24:27.380
within a collection of
manuscript fragments donated

00:24:27.380 --> 00:24:31.780
to the cathedral archives by the
family of Friar Maurio Inguanez

00:24:31.780 --> 00:24:36.580
who remember was the librarian
and archivist of Montecassino.

00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:42.270
This very rare 11th or 12th
century manuscript includes

00:24:42.270 --> 00:24:44.370
within it a unique
blend of Beneventan

00:24:44.370 --> 00:24:46.570
and Carolingian paleography.

00:24:46.570 --> 00:24:51.220
And it is to my mind probably no
doubt made provisionally at least,

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:54.590
provisionally made at the
[inaudible] of Montecassino

00:24:54.590 --> 00:24:59.430 position:56%
and brought to Malta by Father
Inguanez after he went to the island

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:04.760 position:56%
in 1948 probably as part of
maintaining and preserving some link

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:07.610
to his [inaudible]
after he left and went

00:25:07.610 --> 00:25:13.590
to the National Library of Malta.

00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:16.990
From these extremely humble
beginnings, we can actually think

00:25:16.990 --> 00:25:21.340
about 50 years of preserving
the patrimony of humanity.

00:25:21.340 --> 00:25:24.160
On over four continents
now, the Hill Museum

00:25:24.160 --> 00:25:27.490
and Manuscript Library has been
preserving collections throughout

00:25:27.490 --> 00:25:28.990
the world.

00:25:28.990 --> 00:25:32.530
Today we are working on
four distinct continents,

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.780
and what I would like to
take a moment to speak

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:37.860
about our culture efforts first
looking at those in the Middle East

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:40.580
and then in Africa at
the [inaudible] and Malta

00:25:40.580 --> 00:25:43.460
because all together
they encompass our effort

00:25:43.460 --> 00:25:46.560
to preserve endangered collections.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.660
And so we've just added
one in Washington,

00:25:48.660 --> 00:25:52.510
D.C. in the upper left hand corner
thanks to the Catholic University

00:25:52.510 --> 00:25:55.810
of America who last week
opened their collection to us

00:25:55.810 --> 00:25:59.380 position:56%
to help preserve the border of
Malta's collection at their library.

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:01.910
They're a very beautiful
and wonderful collection.

00:26:01.910 --> 00:26:05.940
I'm going to begin
with a brief discussion

00:26:05.940 --> 00:26:11.860
of our preservation efforts
in Syria, which began in 2004

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:15.730
with an inheritance of a project
begun by Brigham Young University.

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:21.840
Our work in these libraries went
from 2004 to 2012 focusing largely

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:24.480
on the collections
and homes in Olimpo

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:28.330
but also few other smaller
collections in the country.

00:26:28.330 --> 00:26:32.370
These projects of course have
been suspended, but in addition

00:26:32.370 --> 00:26:35.380
to our work there, several
of these collections

00:26:35.380 --> 00:26:37.470
at least we believe might
have been relocated.

00:26:37.470 --> 00:26:40.400
We simply do not know at this time.

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:45.580
What we do know is that we have
preserved nearly 3000 manuscripts

00:26:45.580 --> 00:26:48.930
which may or may not have been
destroyed from the city of Olimpo,

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:51.860
the surrounding villages and homes.

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:56.400
All of these collections are
now being kept digitally at HMML

00:26:56.400 --> 00:26:59.610
and remain an important
cultural repository

00:26:59.610 --> 00:27:03.470
for the work not only done
by the librarians at the time

00:27:03.470 --> 00:27:08.820 position:56%
but by the continuing efforts of
our catalogers throughout the world.

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:15.530
A second collection,
of course, is Iraq.

00:27:15.530 --> 00:27:21.220 position:56%
We began filming in Iraq in 2003 and
filming and digitization continues

00:27:21.220 --> 00:27:24.850
to take place primarily in
the city of [inaudible].

00:27:24.850 --> 00:27:29.440
Our preservation efforts began
in Mosul and in [inaudible],

00:27:29.440 --> 00:27:31.160
two cities which of
course now remain

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:34.840
under occupation by
the Islamic state.

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:39.000
We did work in other cities
in Iraq and also in Baghdad,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.260 position:56%
but primarily our effort is
focused on the Christian communities

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:45.270
which have been located in
their endangered collections

00:27:45.270 --> 00:27:48.660
in northwestern Iraq in
the province of Ninevah.

00:27:50.020 --> 00:27:51.520 position:56%
This effort is largely being carried

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:54.880
out by Father Najib
who's a Dominican

00:27:54.880 --> 00:27:57.830
who now is continuing
work in [inaudible].

00:27:57.830 --> 00:28:01.320 position:56%
He's a rather remarkable man because
he spends his mornings taking care

00:28:01.320 --> 00:28:04.710
of the refugees who are living
in [inaudible] and his afternoons

00:28:04.710 --> 00:28:08.770
and evenings as you can see here
preparing these extremely beautiful

00:28:08.770 --> 00:28:11.960
manuscripts for digitization.

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:15.330
This project is being
done in concert

00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:18.370
with the Centre Numerique
des Manuscrits Orientaux,

00:28:18.370 --> 00:28:21.290
the [inaudible] project
and as I'll show you

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:25.890
in just a few moments it has done
some of the remarkable digitization

00:28:25.890 --> 00:28:30.040
in both Turkey and in
Iraq over the last decade.

00:28:30.040 --> 00:28:36.540
A third major project, our largest
project, is taking place currently

00:28:36.540 --> 00:28:39.590
in Mali in the city of [inaudible].

00:28:39.590 --> 00:28:44.030
That is because in 2012 there
was the Taureg Rebellion

00:28:44.030 --> 00:28:45.600
which invaded the city.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:48.100
Many of you might be familiar
with the recently published book,

00:28:48.100 --> 00:28:51.910 position:56%
the [inaudible] Librarians of
Timbuktu, which recounts the efforts

00:28:51.910 --> 00:28:56.560 position:56%
of the local population of
librarians to transport over 50,000,

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:00.500
some even say up to 300,000
manuscripts from Timbuktu

00:29:00.500 --> 00:29:04.510
to [inaudible] in order to
preserve those manuscripts.

00:29:05.540 --> 00:29:09.190
Now, the Hill Museum and
Manuscript Library has been working

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:12.650
with several organizations
in Mali and in [inaudible].

00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:15.710
Here you can see the wonderful
chess that were created

00:29:15.710 --> 00:29:20.450
to ship these manuscripts
to the capital.

00:29:20.450 --> 00:29:25.950
We have now 12 cameras operating
in the city funded by a variety

00:29:25.950 --> 00:29:29.010
of different organizations
including the Arcadia Fund,

00:29:29.010 --> 00:29:32.310
the Prince Claus Fund, the
Juma Al-Majid Center of Culture

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:35.610
and Heritage all working
with SAVAMA-DCI

00:29:35.610 --> 00:29:38.640
to preserve these manuscript
collections.

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:44.780
We are, of course, working
in Malta, and I know Malta

00:29:44.780 --> 00:29:48.490
of course is not currently
underneath any formal threat of war

00:29:48.490 --> 00:29:51.930
or invasion, but it still suffers
from the tremendous effects

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:54.370
of World War II upon the island.

00:29:54.370 --> 00:29:56.940
And here I am speaking
of the Notarial archieves

00:29:56.940 --> 00:29:59.550
in St. Christopher
Street in Valetta.

00:29:59.550 --> 00:30:01.610
The remarkable effort being led

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:04.150
by Dr. Jonah Bella [assumed
spelling] the Notoarial Research

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:09.320
Council to basically help restore
literally thousands and thousands

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:13.200
and thousands of manuscripts dating
back to the 15th century in Malta

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:16.320
which were buried underneath
the city and forgotten as a part

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:19.230
of their attempt to preserve those
records during the bombing raids

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:21.950
of Valetta in world War II.

00:30:21.950 --> 00:30:25.870
The Hill Museum and Manuscript
Library pioneered a project

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:31.750
with the Notarial archieves between
2010 and 2014, and the register

00:30:31.750 --> 00:30:33.620
which you see here, register 202,

00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:38.210
which is a 16th century Notarial
document, has shrapnel holes

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:40.420
in it made by 200 pound
bomb dropped by [inaudible]

00:30:40.420 --> 00:30:43.070
on top of Valetta in 1943.

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:48.330
So you can actually see those are
the bomb fragments that helped --

00:30:48.330 --> 00:30:50.840
that damaged the manuscript.

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:52.930
Thankfully, the European Union

00:30:52.930 --> 00:30:57.350
and the European Council have
recently rewarded the Notarial

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.450
archives with a significant grant

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:03.120
to not only help preserve these
manuscripts but to catalogue them

00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:07.790
and make them available
to the public.

00:31:07.790 --> 00:31:12.610
Another major collection in Malta,
which was discovered in 2010

00:31:12.610 --> 00:31:15.190
which was part of our work with
the National Archives of Malta

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:19.490
between 2007 and 2015 were
an important collection

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:25.120 position:56%
of documents located in
[inaudible] at the front of Valetta.

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:33.340
Here in [inaudible] 2010 literally
probably somewhere around 10,000

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:37.150
to 15,000 manuscript documents were
found at the bottom of a cistern

00:31:37.150 --> 00:31:40.280
where they were dumped
or put in order

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:43.600
to protect the documents during
the bombing raids of World War II.

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:49.710
As you can see, here's a beautiful
40 mm [inaudible] which was located

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:53.100
about 50 meters away from where
these documents were found.

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:57.120
Obviously, a target for any
German bomber at the time.

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:00.590
These manuscripts were discovered
in 2010 and were in such a state

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:03.890
that the Army, the Maltese
Army needed to be brought

00:32:03.890 --> 00:32:08.720
in using chemical suits to remove
the documents from the cistern

00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:11.270
and through the efforts of the
National Archives were able

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:15.840 position:56%
to be cleaned and preserved, and the
Hill Museum and Manuscript Library

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:18.480
and Malta Study Center
helped catalogue

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:25.320
and digitize these records
in the fall of 2015.

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:28.440
Currently in Malta, we
are working with a project

00:32:28.440 --> 00:32:32.720
of Fondazzjoni Patrimonju Malti to
help preserve private libraries.

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:36.780
Private libraries are extremely
vulnerable not simply to forms

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:43.080
of war, but in particular
to sell disbursement

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:45.530
or through issues of
climate control.

00:32:45.530 --> 00:32:48.860
We will be engaging over
the next three to five years

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:52.040 position:56%
in the digitization and preservation
of these vast collections

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:56.620
of libraries, primarily the
repositories of noble families.

00:32:56.620 --> 00:33:00.090
We're currently working at
the [inaudible] in Valetta

00:33:00.090 --> 00:33:05.270
where we have found over 400
manuscripts and 300 archival boxes

00:33:05.270 --> 00:33:09.100
with manuscripts dating
from the early 15th century

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:11.510
through the 20th century.

00:33:11.510 --> 00:33:13.760
These collections are not
simply Maltese collections

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:16.260
but European collections
as the family --

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:20.340
the [inaudible] family held
important positions in France,

00:33:20.340 --> 00:33:25.300
Italy and in the Mediterranean
as Naval captains,

00:33:25.300 --> 00:33:27.690
and they chart the history
of the Mediterranean.

00:33:27.690 --> 00:33:30.220
One of the most amazing
documents that we were able

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:33.970
to find was this beautiful
collection of Lebanese documents

00:33:33.970 --> 00:33:36.730
that were suing the knights
of Malta in the 1730's

00:33:36.730 --> 00:33:40.430 position:56%
to have their cargo restored to them
after it had been illegally seized

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:42.740
in their minds by Maltese
[inaudible].

00:33:42.740 --> 00:33:46.730
The [inaudible] family being
quite wise bought the legal suit

00:33:46.730 --> 00:33:50.200
from the Lebanese family and
proceeded to win the case in court.

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:52.770
Some 30,000 [inaudible]
were delivered

00:33:52.770 --> 00:33:55.120
to the [inaudible] as
part of the process.

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:57.870
This is actually an image as a
part of the legal proceedings

00:33:57.870 --> 00:34:00.820
where they're trying to chart
the Maltese ships hitting --

00:34:00.820 --> 00:34:03.710
about to capture that poor
Lebanese sailing vessel.

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:12.210
Before I move on, I want to
say that all of this done --

00:34:12.210 --> 00:34:16.050
all of the work we've done should
be reminded that every library

00:34:16.050 --> 00:34:18.670
that we worked in, whether
it was vulnerable to war

00:34:18.670 --> 00:34:21.070
or not remains vulnerable.

00:34:21.070 --> 00:34:27.450
We did microfilm the Cologne
State Archives back in the 1980's,

00:34:27.450 --> 00:34:30.940
and as a great tragedy, I
believe according to a gas leak,

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:33.890
the Cologne State Archives
collapsed in 2009.

00:34:33.890 --> 00:34:35.940
And thanks to our microfilming
efforts,

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:38.610
we preserved the Medieval
collection which by

00:34:38.610 --> 00:34:42.670
and large was destroyed during
the collapse of the building.

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:48.510
What does this all mean?

00:34:48.510 --> 00:34:51.490
It means a significant amount
for the preserving of culture

00:34:51.490 --> 00:34:56.500
of our patrimony or
patrimony of humanity.

00:34:56.500 --> 00:34:59.730
Results from our work
in Iraq and Syria alone,

00:34:59.730 --> 00:35:04.210
we've preserved ten collections and
nearly 2000 manuscripts in Mosul,

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:07.230
846 manuscripts in Baghdad.

00:35:07.230 --> 00:35:10.470
In Aleppo itself, nearly
3000 manuscripts.

00:35:10.470 --> 00:35:12.860
Between Iraq and Syria,

00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:16.080
8000 manuscripts have
been digitally preserved

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:17.540
that have been vulnerable to war.

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:24.120
If we put that into the larger
context of the Middle East,

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:28.310
if we add Lebanon and
Jerusalem, Turkey and Egypt,

00:35:28.310 --> 00:35:32.380
nearly 21,000 manuscripts
dating back

00:35:32.380 --> 00:35:36.520
to the middle ages have
been preserved by HMML.

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:43.590
If we think about this in
perspective, what this means

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:47.260
as a repository of
humanity, and I'm sitting here

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:51.010
in probably the world's
greatest repository of knowledge

00:35:51.010 --> 00:35:57.400
that there is, we have
36,600 digitized manuscripts

00:35:57.400 --> 00:36:01.120
from the Middle East,
which is larger than all

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:05.570
of western libraries combined
in Europe and North America.

00:36:05.570 --> 00:36:10.170
If we think about the
Syriac collection alone,

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:15.910
13,500 manuscripts are now being
preserved and catalogued at HMML

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:18.020
where all of the European libraries

00:36:18.020 --> 00:36:21.550
and North American
libraries preserve only 3400

00:36:21.550 --> 00:36:24.100
within their repositories.

00:36:25.930 --> 00:36:30.510
For Islamic culture, the
numbers are no less remarkable.

00:36:30.510 --> 00:36:34.200
31,992 manuscripts and growing.

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:37.930
We think we'll have nearly
100,000 manuscripts preserved

00:36:37.930 --> 00:36:40.340
in the next five years alone.

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:48.130 position:56%
It will be the largest collection
of Islamic manuscripts in the world.

00:36:48.130 --> 00:36:51.590
Malta is a significant
contributor to this project.

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:57.470 position:56%
We've been working in Malta since
1973, and as I say, uninterruptedly.

00:36:57.470 --> 00:37:00.250
If we think about the cathedral
itself which was largely

00:37:00.250 --> 00:37:04.210
in microfilm, 15,000 manuscripts
charting the history of Malta

00:37:04.210 --> 00:37:07.150
through the 15th century
through the 20th century

00:37:07.150 --> 00:37:10.540
and parish archives had
been preserved by HMML.

00:37:10.540 --> 00:37:13.580
This is extremely important because
the Maltese population dispersed

00:37:13.580 --> 00:37:16.970 position:56%
after World War II largely as a
result of the poverty of the country

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:19.720
as it suffered from
the effects of the war.

00:37:19.720 --> 00:37:23.420
I had received daily letters
from Maltese, from Australia,

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:26.500
through Canada, through South
America all looking to us

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:29.890
for their parish records in order
to trace their family history.

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:36.380
The National Library of Malta,
nearly 3500 manuscripts.

00:37:36.380 --> 00:37:38.090
And you can see from
the digital collection,

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:41.370
we now have 3000 manuscripts
themselves.

00:37:41.370 --> 00:37:42.920
This, of course, is a bit deceiving

00:37:42.920 --> 00:37:45.250
because we're largely
preserving archival documents

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:47.380
and archival documents
are much larger

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:49.490
than a traditional manuscript.

00:37:49.490 --> 00:37:53.350
So if we can think of nearly 21,000
manuscripts, it's probably closer

00:37:53.350 --> 00:37:57.600
